# 1. Introduction

Operating systems are one of the most important components of a computer system because they manage hardware resources, coordinate software execution, and provide communication between the user and the machine. Modern operating systems perform several responsibilities such as process management, thread synchronization, memory management, scheduling, and interprocess communication.

The EduOS Operating System Simulator project was developed to demonstrate how these important operating system concepts work in practice. The project combines the C programming language and Python programming language to simulate the behavior of an operating system environment.

The C component focuses mainly on low-level system concepts such as process creation, thread management, synchronization, race conditions, mutexes, semaphores, and interprocess communication. The Python component focuses on CPU scheduling algorithms and system control integration.

The purpose of this project is not to build a fully functional operating system, but rather to create a simulator that demonstrates how operating systems manage resources and coordinate tasks internally.

The simulator was designed to help improve understanding of:

* Process management
* CPU scheduling
* Thread synchronization
* Interprocess communication
* Race conditions
* Shared memory
* Pipes
* Scheduling algorithms
* System integration

The project also demonstrates practical implementation skills in systems programming using structured modular development.


