# 8. CPU Scheduling Algorithms

CPU scheduling determines how processes are assigned CPU execution time.

The EduOS simulator implements four scheduling algorithms using Python.

## 8.1 First Come First Serve (FCFS)

FCFS executes processes in the order they arrive.

Characteristics:

* Simple implementation
* Non-preemptive
* Processes execute sequentially

Advantages:

* Easy to implement
* Fair based on arrival order

Disadvantages:

* Long waiting time
* Convoy effect
* Poor response time

The simulator calculates execution intervals for each process.

## 8.2 Shortest Job First (SJF)

SJF executes the process with the smallest burst time first.

Characteristics:

* Optimizes average waiting time
* Efficient for short processes

Advantages:

* Better turnaround time
* Improved efficiency

Disadvantages:

* Starvation may occur
* Burst prediction may be difficult

The simulator sorts processes based on burst time before execution.

## 8.3 Priority Scheduling

Priority scheduling executes processes according to priority level.

Characteristics:

* Higher priority processes execute first
* Useful for critical tasks

Advantages:

* Supports important processes
* Flexible scheduling control

Disadvantages:

* Low priority starvation
* Requires proper priority management

The simulator sorts processes according to priority values.

## 8.4 Round Robin Scheduling

Round Robin scheduling allocates CPU time using time slices called quantum.

Characteristics:

* Preemptive scheduling
* Fair CPU allocation
* Suitable for multitasking systems

Advantages:

* Good response time
* Fair process execution
* Prevents starvation

Disadvantages:

* High context switching overhead
* Performance depends on quantum size

The simulator repeatedly cycles through processes until all processes complete execution.


